# PART I ‚Äî DESIGN DOC

## Purpose
Novel candidates (esp. non-tree architectures) are first-draft solutions that get dominated out
by the hand-tuned frontier before they can be refined ‚Äî so every Bedrock dollar the `novelty`
operator spends is wasted by design. The grace period gives each novel lineage a **bounded,
fair trial**: for a short window after birth, its descendants are up-weighted as parents so they
get refined a few times before the frontier judges them on merit.

**Dual purpose (equally important):** produce a *defensible negative result*. If protected novel
lineages still can't reach the frontier after a fair trial, that is a reportable finding ‚Äî "we
refined each novel architecture and it genuinely fell short" ‚Äî which certifies the incumbent
(e.g. decision tree) rather than leaving "did we even try?" ambiguous. The grace period is what
makes that claim honest.

## Prerequisite (confirmed shipped)
- Serialization fix (sys.path Option A) is in ‚Äî non-tree candidates survive to evaluation. A
  grace period would be meaningless otherwise (it would protect a lineage of crashes).

## Locked decisions

### G1 ‚Äî Window semantics: absolute-N (option "a")
Protect each novel lineage for a fixed **N tries after its birth**, then it reverts to a normal
frontier-ruled candidate.
- **N = 3** (absolute, not a fraction of horizon).
- Chosen over per-lineage-refinement-count (b), quota (d), and promise-gated (e) because it needs
  the **least tracking machinery** (see G3) and its mechanism transfers to MAP-Elites (see
  "Forward reuse"); (b)/(e) stay as graduations if absolute-N proves too crude.
- **Accepted tradeoff:** absolute N is not scale-invariant ‚Äî 3 tries is a third of a 10-try run
  and 3% of a 100-try run. Acceptable because runs are fixed-size in practice; revisit if run
  sizes vary widely.

### G2 ‚Äî Protection mechanism: selection up-weight, not binary eligibility
A protected lineage is **up-weighted as a parent** relative to frontier members ‚Äî NOT a binary
on/off "eligible even if off-frontier" gate.
- **Flat multiplier (base form):** protected candidates get a higher selection weight than a
  normal frontier member. **Refined in G5:** the weight scales with frontier size rather than
  being an absolute constant. One knob (`NOVELTY_PROTECT_WEIGHT`).
- Chosen over additive bonus and over decay-over-N because: composes cleanly with crowding
  distance later (both are just multipliers on selection weight), and one knob. Decay (fade-out
  instead of a cliff at expiry) is the graduation if the expiry cliff turns out to matter at N=3.

### G3 ‚Äî Tracking: inherited provenance tag + quasi-lineage id (sub-feature)
Each candidate carries a small **inherited provenance tag**, propagated parent‚Üíchild. Built as a
**sub-feature of this grace-period work** (not a standalone project), but designed general enough
to be reused later (multi-init, MAP-Elites, negative-result reporting).

Tag fields:
- `origin` ‚Äî what produced this candidate (e.g. "novelty", "improve", "seed").
- `born_try` ‚Äî the try index at which this candidate was created.
- `lineage_id` ‚Äî **set once at a lineage's birth and inherited UNCHANGED by every descendant**
  (unlike `parent_try_id`, which changes each generation). This is the whole quasi-lineage
  mechanism: grouping candidates by lineage is a **filter on `lineage_id`**, not a graph
  traversal. A `novelty` birth starts a new `lineage_id`; an `improve` child keeps its parent's.

**Scope = "quasi-lineage" (rung 2), explicitly NOT full genealogy (rung 3).** We can answer
"what produced this / what family is it / show the family's trajectory" by reading a field or a
group-by. We do NOT build parent-pointer traversal, ancestor queries, or a DAG engine ‚Äî that's
deferred until MAP-Elites (or another feature) actually forces it (primer: no speculative
abstraction).

**Combine inheritance rule (the one real fork, resolved):** a combined child has two parents,
possibly with different `lineage_id`s. Rule **(a)**: if **either** parent is a novel/protected
lineage, the child inherits **that** lineage's id; otherwise inherit the first parent's id
(deterministic). Rationale: a novel lineage that gets merged via `combine` should keep its
provenance ‚Äî combine is a plausible path for a novel architecture to survive into the frontier,
and the negative-result report wants "this novelty lineage contributed via try X" rather than the
trail going cold. (Fresh-id and compound-id rejected: fresh loses the novelty trail; compound is
more than a sub-feature needs.)

Protection check stays **local**: read the candidate's own `born_try`,
`current_try - born_try < NOVELTY_PROTECT_N`. No aggregation needed for the window itself;
`lineage_id` grouping is for reporting/reuse, not the protection test.

## Forward reuse (why this substrate, not throwaway)
The provenance tag (G3) ‚Äî an inherited, self-describing descriptor read locally at selection time
‚Äî is the same instrument needed by:
- **multi-init** ‚Äî attribute each candidate to its origin seed (for fair trials + negative report),
- **MAP-Elites** ‚Äî niche/behavior key per candidate (read locally, no aggregation),
- **negative-result reporting** ‚Äî group candidates by origin to show each family's trajectory.
The grace-period *logic* (G1/G2) is throwaway (MAP-Elites replaces temporary protection with
permanent best-in-niche protection), but the *provenance instrument* (G3) carries forward. The
grace period is the cheapest first customer for provenance tracking, which is the real missing
instrument under most of the roadmap. (Crowding distance is the one parked ablation that does NOT
use it ‚Äî it operates on frontier positions, not provenance.)

## Constants (named, commented; per project convention ‚Äî no magic literals)
- `NOVELTY_PROTECT_N = 3` ‚Äî tries a novel lineage stays protected after birth.
- `NOVELTY_PROTECT_WEIGHT = <TBD>` ‚Äî protection strength, expressed **relative to frontier size**
  (G5), not an absolute pick-weight. Exact use defined in recipe.

### G4 ‚Äî Scope: `improve` parent selection only
The protection up-weight (G2) applies **only to `improve`'s parent selection**. `combine`
(`pick_frontier_extremes`) and `repair` are untouched.
- Rationale: the grace period's purpose is *refinement* of young lineages ‚Äî exactly what
  `improve` does. `combine` deliberately selects diverse frontier extremes; injecting a
  protected off-frontier candidate would distort that logic and require touching
  `pick_frontier_extremes`. Keeping protection to `improve` is targeted and additive.

### G5 ‚Äî Up-weight mechanism: extend improve's pool + weight, scaled to frontier size
`improve`'s parent selection is today **uniform-random over the frontier** (no weights).
Protection changes this to:
- **Pool = frontier members ‚à™ currently-protected candidates** (protected candidates eligible
  even when off-frontier ‚Äî the point of protection).
- **Weighted pick** (not uniform): protected candidates get higher pick probability than normal
  frontier members.
- **Weight scales with frontier size, not an absolute constant.** A flat multiplier's relative
  boost decays as the frontier grows (more members dilute the pool); expressing protection
  strength relative to frontier size keeps a protected lineage's effective shot roughly constant
  whether the frontier has 3 or 30 members. Exact formula deferred to the recipe.
- **[SCOUT]** confirm `select_parent`'s current form; this extends it from "uniform over frontier"
  to "weighted over frontier ‚à™ protected" ‚Äî the one real structural change (rest additive).

### G6 ‚Äî Provenance/quasi-lineage tag is a prerequisite sub-build (built first)
The inherited provenance tag + `lineage_id` (G3) do **not** exist in the core loop today. The
recipe builds this **sub-feature** first, before the protection logic:
- Minimal tag: `origin`, `born_try`, `lineage_id` ‚Äî set at candidate creation, inherited
  parent‚Üíchild, with the combine rule (a) from G3.
- Kept to rung 2 (group-by, no traversal); reusable by multi-init / MAP-Elites / negative-report,
  but NOT extracted into a standalone feature/framework ‚Äî it's a sub-feature of this work.
- **Recipe ordering:** Chunk 1 = provenance/lineage tag ‚Üí Chunk 2 = protection logic (protection
  reads `born_try`).

## Open forks (still to decide)
- **`NOVELTY_PROTECT_WEIGHT` value + exact formula** ‚Äî falls out of the real `select_parent`
  internals (SCOUT in G5).
- **Tag write-sites (SCOUT)** ‚Äî (1) where a candidate is created so the tag is set; (2) how
